PROBLEM STATEMENT 2:-¶

WHAT IS THE PERCENTAGE OF THE AFFECTED (GENDERWISE):-

In [9]:
gender=ds1.gender
gender.dropna(inplace=True)
gender=gender.value_counts()
per=[]
for i in gender:
    perc=i/gender.sum()
    per.append(format(perc,'.2f'))
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))    
plt.title('Comparing cases according to gender',fontsize=20)
plt.pie(per,autopct='%1.1f%%')
plt.legend(gender.index,loc='best',title='Gender',fontsize=15)
plt.show()

OBSERVATION:-¶

India has reported a 70.0% in men while only a 30.0% rate in women due to COVID-19, according to the data provided . While the number of people infected is almost equal in number, it is the women who have a comparatively more survival rate than men.¶

A number of factors may be working against men in the current situation such as lifestyle activities, biological reasons and even immunity system. When it comes to mounting an immune response against infections, men are the weaker sex. Yes, you read that right. Women have a greater ability to fight against infections and diseases than men.¶

In addition to all the working women are less than the men in india that's why women are less infected to the corona virus wrt to the men.¶

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

confirmed1=ds2['Total Confirmed cases'].sum()
death=ds2['Death'].sum()
recovered=ds2['Cured/Discharged/Migrated'].sum()
lables=['confirmed','death','recovered']
total = [confirmed1,death,recovered]

fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots()
ax1.pie(total,labels=lables, autopct='%1.1f%%')
ax1.axis('equal')  # Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle.
plt.legend(total,loc='best',title='current status',fontsize=15)
plt.show()

The recovery rate of coronavirus patients in India had further risen to 12.1% with a total of 2231 patients getting discharged so far and the list of districts that have not reported any new Covid-19 cases in the past two weeks rising to 56, the Union government said on Saturday while highlighting the positive results emerging from country’s fight against the contagion.¶

The recovery rate was nearly 13% as per government figures released on Friday last week, which was a steady improvement from the previous week’s 8%¶

OBSERVATION:-¶

1. Given that testing has been uneven across the country, it is difficult to say to what extent the reporting of cases across regions reflects actual incidence, and to what extent it reflects the scale of testing. If the extent of under-reporting is not high and the confirmed cases reflect the true spread of covid-19 in India, it could simply imply the better integration of urbanized and densely packed districts with the rest of the country and the world. In normal years, these features make these districts attractive destinations for migrants.¶

2. the first coronavirus case was also confirmed in Mumbai’s Dharavi slum, which is India’s largest and is home to almost one million people living in close, unsanitary quarters.¶

3. All above are the reason for the deaths in urban cities.¶

Observation:-¶

1.The novel coronavirus has so far infected mostly the working-age population in India. The Union health ministry said that an age-wise analysis of coronavirus patients in India shows that more than 42 per cent of them belong to the age group of 21-40.¶

2. The next most-hit age group is those between ages 41 and 50, which compromises of 33 per cent of the Covid-19 positive cases in the country.¶

3.Senior citizens (60+), who are otherwise the most high-risk group for the viral infection, form 17 per cent of the Covid-19 patient group in India.¶

4. Only 9 per cent of those below 20 years of age have been found to be coronavirus positive, the health ministry said.¶

5. The ministry's analysis confirms an India Today Data Intelligence Unit report that found that the novel coronavirus has so far infected mostly the working-age population in India.¶

6.Young Indians are at higher risk of contracting the disease as 83 per cent of the patients are under the age of 50.¶
